The paper deals with the problem of voter control in elections, which is a topic in computational social choice (cs.GT). The introduction of the concept of sequential elections and the analysis of the complexity of the related problems suggest a focus on algorithmic aspects, which are also relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of computational complexity theory to analyze the hardness of the problems suggests a connection to theoretical computer science (cs.CC). The modeling of the problem as a decision problem and the analysis of the complexity classes suggest a focus on algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the use of machine learning techniques to analyze the data and make predictions suggests a connection to machine learning (cs.LG).
